{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Dard-e-Ishq\" (\"The Anguish of Love\"), the pain of love—personified directly as \"O, Anguish of Love!\"—is characterized as a radiant and pure entity, likened to \"a pearl of purest water,\" whose intrinsic value demands it remain concealed from unworthy (\"unperceived\") eyes and the superficiality of the modern world.[^1][^2] It is portrayed as sacred and veiled, incompatible with public display, the \"new assembly\" that chases \"surface light,\" scientific rationalism, critical scrutiny, or shallow spectacles; instead, it belongs hidden in the \"soul's most secret receptacle,\" unexpressed through poetry, music, or outward grief.[^3][^4][^5] The poem urges this anguish to withdraw entirely from an age where hearts are \"drunk on wines of its own mind,\" finding no place or joy amid life's corrupted \"once-sacred grounds.\"[^6]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Dard-e-Ishq\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/17-dard-e-ishq/translation/#p-6d19d8).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Dard-e-Ishq\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/17-dard-e-ishq/translation/#p-b75085).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Dard-e-Ishq\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/17-dard-e-ishq/translation/#p-3d4e57).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Dard-e-Ishq\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/17-dard-e-ishq/translation/#p-71e687).\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Dard-e-Ishq\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/17-dard-e-ishq/translation/#p-463ab2).\n\n[^6]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Dard-e-Ishq\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/17-dard-e-ishq/translation/#p-d85ab0).",
